ğŸ”¶ 1. STRUCTURE: DEFINITION, SYNTAX & BASIC OPERATIONS
ğŸ”¹ What is a Structure?
A structure in C is a user-defined data type that allows grouping variables of different data types under a single name.

ğŸ‘‰ Syntax:
struct StructureName {
    dataType member1;
    dataType member2;
    ...
};


ğŸ‘‰ Example:
struct Student {
    int id;
    char name[50];
    float marks;
};


ğŸ”¹ Declaration of Structure Variable:
struct Student s1;  // Without typedef

ğŸ”¹ Typedef Declaration:
typedef struct Student {
    int id;
    char name[50];
    float marks;
} Student;

Student s1; // Now we can use 'Student' instead of 'struct Student'



ğŸ”¹ Initialization of Structure:
struct Student s1 = {101, "Ashika", 98.5};

ğŸ”¹ Accessing Members (using . and ->):

ğŸ‘‰Using dot operator
printf("ID: %d", s1.id);

ğŸ‘‰ Using arrow operator with pointer
struct Student *ptr = &s1;
printf("Name: %s", ptr->name);


ğŸ”¹ Copying Structure:
    struct Student s2 = s1;  // Entire structure copy

    
ğŸ”¹ Comparing Structure:
ğŸ”¸ Structures cannot be compared directly using ==.
if (s1.id == s2.id && strcmp(s1.name, s2.name) == 0)
    printf("Structures are equal");





    
ğŸ”¶ 2. NESTED STRUCTURE
A structure inside another structure.

struct Date {
    int day, month, year;
};
struct Student {
    int id;
    char name[50];
    struct Date dob; // Nested structure
};

âœ… Accessing nested members:
struct Student s = {101, "Ashika", {1, 1, 2000}};
printf("%d/%d/%d", s.dob.day, s.dob.month, s.dob.year);







ğŸ”¶ 3. ARRAY OF STRUCTURES
You can store multiple structure variables in an array.

struct Student {
    int id;
    char name[50];
    float marks;
};
int main() {
    struct Student s[3];
    for (int i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
        printf("Enter ID, Name, Marks: ");
        scanf("%d %s %f", &s[i].id, s[i].name, &s[i].marks);
    }
}




ğŸ”¶ 4. STRUCTURE AND FUNCTION

ğŸ”¹ Passing Individual Members:
void printDetails(int id, char name[]) {
    printf("ID: %d, Name: %s", id, name);
}


ğŸ”¹ Passing Entire Structure (by value):
void printStudent(struct Student s) {
    printf("ID: %d Name: %s", s.id, s.name);
}

ğŸ”¹ Passing Structure via Pointer:
void printStudentPtr(struct Student *s) {
    printf("ID: %d Name: %s", s->id, s->name);
}

ğŸ”¶ 5. SELF-REFERENTIAL STRUCTURE
A structure that contains a pointer to a structure of the same type. Used in linked lists.

struct Node {
    int data;
    struct Node *next;  // Self-referential
};
